        1.7  PAGES


        Lines are automatically separated  into  pages  by  RNF.   Two
        control the size of RNF pages: .PS (Page Size) and .LINES.

        The first argument of .PS  specifies  the  number  of  lines  wh
        allowed  on  a page before an automatic page throw is done.  Thi
        includes the lines in the header at the top of each page, and th
        text  on the page, but does not include the lines in the footer
        at the bottom of the page.  The .LINES command specifies the  nu
        lines  on  the  entire  page.   This number is used when simulat
        ejects on terminals with continuous forms.

        The default .PS first argument and .LINES are 58 and  66,  respe
        This allows at least a 1 and 1/3 inch bottom margin with 6 line
        printing, and a 1 inch margin with line per inch  printing  on
        CSO reduced forms.

        Some terminals use reduced forms but print 6 lines per inch.  Th
        there are 51 lines on each page; a .PS first argument of 44 will
        1 inch bottom margin.



        1.7.1  Explicit paging control


        The  .PAGE  command  allows  the  user  to  advance  to  the  ne
        explicitly.   The .NMP and .PNO commands control page numbering,
        .TITLE, .ST, and .ATITLE commands provide for printing titles at
        of each page.



        1.7.2  Page Format


        A page is divided into three areas:

           . The top, which contains the upper margin and  optional  tit
             page number.

